    "fresh": true,
    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 19, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🚢 Iran Closed the Strait of Hormuz Again. The \"Ceasefire\" Didn't Last the Weekend.\n\nIran announced it is again shutting down the Strait of Hormuz, citing US \"breaches of trust\" during ceasefire negotiations — one day after the Lebanon ceasefire lasted approximately 30 minutes.\n\n- **The trigger:** Iran blames the US for failing to honor commitments made during the April 17 ceasefire window. The US naval blockade on Iran remains in place. Oil prices are doing what oil prices do when Hormuz closes.\n- **The stakes:** About 20% of the world's oil passes through this strait. Every closure spirals energy markets, reroutes shipping around Africa, and multiplies insurance premiums. None of this is new information.\n\n*\"Very close to a deal\" — Trump, April 8. Trump, April 17. Presumably Trump, April 19.*\n\n**Sources:** [CNN](https://www.cnn.com/2026/04/18/world/live-news/iran-war-trump-israel)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 The EU Wants Companies to Prove Their AI Doesn't Discriminate in Hiring. In 105 Days.\n\nEuropean regulators confirmed on April 19 the exact scope, documentation requirements, and timeline for AI hiring bias audits under the EU AI Act — with 105 days remaining before compliance becomes mandatory.\n\n- **What's required:** Companies using AI in hiring decisions must conduct formal bias audits and maintain documentation covering resume screening, interview scoring, and automated hiring tools.\n- **The timeline pressure:** The EU AI Act's high-risk provisions have been known since 2024. The 105-day countdown implies a lot of HR tech vendors are just now opening the compliance checklist.\n\n*\"We'll deal with it when we have to\" apparently has a due date, and it's August.*\n\n**Sources:** [Asanify](https://asanify.com/blog/news/ai-hiring-bias-audit-april-19-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🇷🇺 Russia Deployed 9,360 Kamikaze Drones in a Single Day\n\nIn one of the largest drone assaults recorded in the Ukraine war, Russia deployed 9,360 kamikaze drones in a single 24-hour period, alongside 153 combat engagements and 68 airstrikes. Over the past year, Russia has captured 1,897 square miles of Ukrainian territory.\n\n- **The scale:** 9,360 drones in one day is no longer a military operation — it's an industrial process. Ukraine's air defenses aren't overwhelmed by capability; they're overwhelmed by throughput.\n- **The year in review:** 1,897 square miles in 12 months. At this rate, the math speaks without editorial commentary.\n\n*The war of attrition is going fine. For one side.*\n\n**Sources:** [Russia Matters](https://www.russiamatters.org/news/russia-ukraine-war-report-card/russia-ukraine-war-report-card-april-15-2026)\n\n---\n\n## 🇧🇬 Bulgaria Held Its Elections Again. Still Five Parties. Still No Clear Path Forward.\n\nBulgaria held another round of early elections on April 19, with five political groups securing parliamentary seats: Progressive Bulgaria, GERB-UDF, We Continue the Change, Movement for Rights and Freedoms, and Vuzrazhdane.\n\n- **The context:** Bulgaria has cycled through inconclusive elections since 2021 with no party able to form a stable majority. Five parties in parliament is the norm; governing with them is not.\n- **The EU angle:** Bulgaria's chronic instability strains eastern-flank cohesion at exactly the moment the Iran war is reshaping regional alignments along NATO's eastern edge.\n\n*Fifteen elections in five years is either a democracy in crisis or very committed civic participation. The Bulgarians seem unsure which.*\n\n**Sources:** [Geopolitical Monitor](https://www.geopoliticalmonitor.com/)\n\n---\n\n## 🕊️ Pakistan Is Now the Go-To Mediator for the Iran-US-Israel War. India Is Watching.\n\nPakistan has emerged as the primary backchannel between Iran and the US-Israeli coalition — hosting negotiations and shuttling messages — while its own relationship with India, frozen since Operation Sindoor (May 2025), quietly continues through back channels.\n\n- **Pakistan's pivot:** After Operation Sindoor, India-Pakistan relations froze publicly. Islamabad pivoted to international diplomacy, gaining unprecedented visibility as a peacemaker in the Iran war while back-channel India talks reportedly continue.\n- **The irony:** A country routinely described as a geopolitical liability is currently doing the diplomatic work no one else wants to do. The Iran talks have given Pakistan a stage it rarely occupies.\n\n*Pakistan became a peace mediator. The timing is interesting.*\n\n**Sources:** [The Week India](https://www.theweek.in/news/defence/2026/04/17/india-pakistan-backchannel-talks-on-despite-freeze-since-operation-sindoor-report.html)"
  }
